<paragraph id="666036ACFFABFFAABDF2B88511118919" blockId="92.[151,1436,1432,1573]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">
<emphasis id="54ABEABEFFABFFAABDF2B88515B88AC2" box="[207,448,1510,1534]" italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Diagnostic characters</emphasis>
: The presence of a single pars ventralis (
<figureCitation id="FEE42A29FFABFFAABE45B88417988AC2" box="[888,992,1510,1534]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="94.[151,250,1591,1614]" captionTargetBox="[252,1331,254,1569]" captionTargetId="figure-237@94.[244,1340,247,1582]" captionTargetPageId="94" captionText="FIGURE 30. Allocladius spp. A–E, A. bothnicus (Tuiskunen), immmatures. A—male genital sheath of pupa; B—larval antenna; C—premandible; D—mandible; E—mentum. F–G, A. scrotus Andersen, Saether et Mendes. F—hypopygium; G— pars ventralis [A–E after Makarchenko &amp; Makarchenko 2007, F–G from Andersen et al. 2010]." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5288335" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5288335/files/figure.png" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Fig. 30 G</figureCitation>
) about twice as wide as long and without setae together with the tongue-like strongly projecting inferior volsella and from other species with pars ventralis.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="666036ACFFABFFAABDAABB391760894F" blockId="92.[151,792,1627,1652]" box="[151,792,1627,1652]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">
